  "text": "For composite message spaces Z N , we can choose t randomly from Z N/2 and set encode(s) = s + 2 · t to encode -bit secrets. Laur and Lipmaa showed that this encoding is 2 −1 /γ-secure where γ is the smallest factor of N and there are no alternative encoding functions with significantly longer secrets [CITATION_1] . See App. A for a more detailed discussion about optimality. This construction can be lifted to the vectorised setting provided that all plaintext components have the same public order n as in [SV11,GHS12,DPSZ12]. To encode s, we first use additive secret sharing to split s into the sum s 1 + · · · + s k and then use encode function for each component s i separately. By the construction, the noise hides at least one component s i if G = {0} and thus the secret s becomes unreconstructable.",
